      <div class="exec-label">The Short Version</div>
      <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Tibetan has over sixty fonts available online — but most of them don't actually work properly. When you test them on real devices, only about a dozen render Tibetan text without visible errors. None were designed for children. None were designed for phone screens. Most are digital copies of hand-drawn letters from the 1990s that were never meant for the modern web.</p>
      <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">The result? Six specific problems that affect every piece of Tibetan digital text:</p>
      <ol style="padding-left:1.5rem; margin-bottom:1rem; font-size:.92rem; color:var(--text2, #94a3b8); line-height:1.9;">
        <li><strong>Ghost circles</strong> — placeholder dots appear inside words when the font doesn't know how to stack certain letters</li>
        <li><strong>Words break in the wrong places</strong> — lines split in the middle of syllables instead of at natural word boundaries</li>
        <li><strong>Letters get cut off</strong> — vowel marks above and below the line are clipped by the text container</li>
        <li><strong>No standard way to load fonts</strong> — every developer reinvents font loading, leading to inconsistent results</li>
        <li><strong>Tibetan and English don't mix</strong> — bilingual text looks broken because the sizes and alignments clash</li>
        <li><strong>The diaspora is losing the script</strong> — children and heritage learners give up because the fonts make the writing look harder than it is</li>
      </ol>
      <p>We are building three new fonts to fix these problems — a formal serif, a clean screen font, and a child-friendly version. All free, forever. The technical details of each problem are documented below.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

